      "id": "review::.::holistic::mid_level_elegance::microsoft_enablement_policy_is_split",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "Microsoft flow availability is recomputed separately at multiple boundaries",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "mid_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/ProviderConfigController.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/AuthController.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/config/MicrosoftAuthorizationGateFilter.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/config/IdentityContractGuard.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/config/MicrosoftAuthProperties.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`ProviderConfigController` decides Microsoft availability by combining rollout flags with `isClientSideConfigured()` and `isServerSideConfigured()`.",
          "`AuthController` separately checks `rolloutProperties.getMicrosoft().isClientSideEnabled()` before challenge/verify and also treats `ObjectProvider<MicrosoftTokenVerifier>` absence as another disablement path.",
          "`MicrosoftAuthorizationGateFilter` and `IdentityContractGuard` each repeat their own Microsoft enablement/configuration checks, so rollout semantics live in several boundary classes."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Move Microsoft availability decisions into one shared policy on the existing config layer (for example canonical `isClientSideAvailable()` / `isServerSideAvailable()` helpers) and have the controller, filter, guard, and provider-config endpoint consume that shared verdict instead of re-deriving it.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "966c22d6"
      },
      "status": "open",
